<br>
Second, I do not have a problem with Bush expressing his religious beliefs.  Everyone has the right to do so.  However, they shouldn't be expressed while fulfilling his presidential duties.  I don't think the Christians would like it if their children had a Muslim teacher who was constantly expressing sentiments in the classroom regarding Islam.  Sure, she can admit she is Muslim, maybe talk about her practices from a cultural standpoint, and answer any question one might have of Islam, but to push it on the class during lectures is a whole different story.  The Christian parents would be up in arms regarding SOCAS issues if that was the case.  Bush is using his power to push his views on the public.  I don't care if he wants to discuss dogma until the cows come home on a Barbara Walters special or something, but when he is standing up and speaking in his government role, he needs to be fair to ALL his constituents, and he needs to keep his beliefs to himself.  I think that some Christians tend to feel that when SOCAS comes up, then we are trampling on their freedom to practice their religion.  I think everyone has a right to practice their religion how they see fit as long as it doesn't harm anyone.  If you need to pray several times a day or read your bible, then fine.  It is just that this religious practice shouldn't be invading the rights of others.  Bush is invading people's religious freedom by pushing his own beliefs off on people when they are expecting him to be discussing national business.  People are feeling duped.  Imagine if your doctor called you in claiming to be discussing medical business, and when you got there he just talked about his religion.  He would be using his power to grab hold of you and try to push off his beliefs.  If I pulled this crap on my clients, my bosses would boot my butt out of this firm.  I don't claim to want to discuss their accounting work and then start talking about Judaism.  I could claim that it is my right to talk about Judaism to my clients under the Constitution, but we all know that it is wrong and unprofessional.  The only thing that prevents it from being unconstitutional is that I work for a private business.  Bush doesn't work for a private business.  He is a governmental official employed by all the taxpayers.  Not Christian taxpayers, but all taxpayers.  And nowhere in the Constitution does it say that people should be forced to live under the rule of Christianity.  Yes, the majority of Americans happen to be Christian, but that is just a matter of demographics.  If this country goes through an enlightenment period and the majority decides to become Hindu, then do we call this place a &quot;Hindu Country&quot;?  Do we sit by while our president discusses his polytheistic beliefs?  Do we send around joke e-mails about being a true American and &quot;anyone who doesn't worship Krishna can just go back to where they came from&quot;?  Do we claim that those who eat beef are now putting a financial strain on others like we currently do with the mythical &quot;kosher tax&quot;?  I think it is real easy to say that this is an {insert religion here} country when you are the majority religion.  I would be real curious to see what happens if the tables ever get turned.<br>
<br>
