<br>
All SOCAS implications aside, do you not consider it remotely insensitive, arrogant, and narrowminded of Bush to say what he said, given the diverse beliefs of the shuttle crew, let alone our nation at large?  I'm wondering how you would feel, honestly, if Lieberman were president and he offered a prayer in Hebrew?  If every time he addressed the nation, he said something about his religion, something exclusively Jewish, something you didn't believe and could not agree with?<br>
<br>
We're all familiar with the Declaration of Independence;  I had to memorize a large portion of it in fifth grade.  Bear in mind that it is *not* law.  The framers of the Constitution convened years later to lay out the groundwork of our federal laws, and expressed their ideas about religion's place in government quite clearly through the first amendment.  Whether or not they, as individuals, believed in a Creator or a God or a Savior is irrelevant.  I'm tired of the argument that, despite the First Amendment, we are an implicitly Christian nation, simply because the men who drafted our Constitution had in some other forum, some other correspondence, professed to hold Christian beliefs. . .   as though &quot;Freedom of Religion&quot; is the result of some legislative oversight.  <br>
<br>
As Gaia said, there are actual &quot;Christian&quot; nations in Europe that have enough respect for citizens of differing beliefs to exclude their own personal religious thoughts when  addressing the nation.  The irony is overwhelming.<br>
<br>
