o lack of funds.  I just had to inform one of my clients the other week that after audit adjustments, they are suffering from a big fat loss.  This is the same organization who has empty shelves sitting down in their food bank.  But yes, let's take more of their funds away and give it to the local church.  We want to make sure that church has plenty of money left over for prayer books after they do their charitable work.  Blech.<br>
<br>
There is also no reason these churches can't be in the business of helping the community as well.  Forming a nonprofit organization isn't rocket science.  If these churches want to receive federal funds, then they could take a few board members and have them form a seperate nonprofit entity.  There is no reason the church has to directly have federal funds, unless of course they want these funds to be used for religious purposes.  The government won't even tell the entity that they can't preach while doing their community service.  I audit one nonprofit who can't even get through a board meeting without prayer.  But at least we know the funds are being used for their intended purpose.  These faith-based initiatives are nothing more than a smoke screen for the right wing religious agenda. <br>
<br>
