<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Government-sponsored memorials that utilize religious prayers or speeches are not merely insensitive, they are unconstitutional: <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>The Supreme Court has ruled that government is not permitted to affirmatively sponsor “the particular religious practice of prayer.” </strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Sante Fe Independent School District v. Doe, 530 U.S. 290, 313 (2000).  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>This is because such activity sends the message to nonadherents that “they are outsiders, not full members of the political community.”</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Id. at 309-10 (quoting Lynch v. Donnelly, 465 U.S. 668, 688 (1984) (O’Connor, J., concurring)).  The inclusion of prayer at official events designed to commemorate September 11th is unconstitutional. <br>
<br>
It naturally follows that state and local governments may not commission “official” prayers for an occasion.  See Lee v. Weisman, 505 U.S. at 588 (1992).  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Indeed, the Court has specifically held that “it is no part of the business of government to compose official prayers for any group of the American people to recite as a part of a religious program carried on by the government.” </strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Engel v. Vitale, 370 U.S. 421, 425 (1962).<br>
<br>
Government cannot bypass these requirements by crafting a prayer that is non-denominational.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>The Supreme Court has held that the First Amendment does not allow the government to commission and promulgate even a “nonsectarian” prayer.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  See Lee, 505 U.S. at 589.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
So yes, once someone enters office and begins speaking <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>for</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> the people, they are expected to leave their religious beliefs behind. <br>
<br>
We expect elected officials to give up their right to privacy, because it is in the interest of the people to know what type of person they are.<br>
