You state you believe that he was insensitive; then you negate this statement by saying that, despite its inherent insensitivity, he should say what he believes because - darn it!- he has freedom of religion.  His freedom of religion, then, in your eyes, supercedes any presidential obligation, any professional responsibility.  <br>
<br>
As Americans, we enjoy a number of freedoms. . . but that doesn't mean that it is always appropriate, fair, or safe - even for private citizens - to employ them.  That is why the Supreme Court interprets the law and sets certain reasonable parameters for freedom.  &quot;Fighting Words&quot; are exceptions to our freedom of speech; the case CAD posted above limits the religious freedom of people in public office while acting in a public capacity.<br>
<br>
I recently read an article about another case involving freedom of expression. . . it dealt with the Mormon Church's attempt to ban what it considered &quot;offensive&quot; speech, T-shirt slogans, and behavior (such as same sex couples holding hands) from the public square in front of the Mormon temple in Salt Lake City.  Funny how you're all worked up about Bush's freedom of religion, while your church is attempting to stomp other people's freedom into the ground.<br>
